// 4-bit Font Sprite Sheet with 4 color LUT

// Font Tilemap to contain most ascii and some extended
// ascii tiles. This is completely created by me junebug12851.
// It was originally designed for the Original Gameboy and fit perfectly
// into the lower-third of Gameboy VRAM area

// I just realized the 1989 Gameboy had twice as much vram
// as the N64..... * facepalm * You know you screwed up
// when a black and white brick gaming system from the 80's
// that deal with tiles has more vram than a mid-late 90's
// 3D powerhouse.

// Was real difficult to convert to N64 format though
// 1) Had to export from gimp as raw data
//    (Index, Alpha)
//
// 2) Then use a hex editor to export is as C
// 3) from there use a regex find/replace to take out the
//    extra alpha byte. 
// 4) Then had to use regex to merge the seperate bytes into 1 (N64 4-bit)
// 5) Then had to copy the LUT table over in appropriate N64 format
// 6) Then I had to write my own program using code from Jason Palmer to convert colors to RGBA 5551
//    https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19076061/converting-rgba8888-to-rgba5551
//    Thanks Jason!

